This paper is likely to belong to the Computer Science sub-category of cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) as it presents a method for differentiating between known and previously unseen malware families, which is a key issue in cybersecurity. The use of deep learning techniques also suggests that it could belong to the sub-categories of cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). Additionally, the paper mentions the use of static and dynamic features of malware, which could indicate that it belongs to the sub-category of cs.CV (Computer Vision) as well. Finally, the paper's focus on improving the ability to adapt to the fast-moving pace of the current threat landscape suggests that it could also belong to the sub-category of cs.SE (Software Engineering).
